00

What is Matplotlib?

Matplotlib is Python's most widely used 2D plotting library, created by John Hunter in 2003. It produces publication-quality figures in a variety of hardcopy formats and interactive environments.

ComponentDescription
matplotlib.pyplotMATLAB-style stateful interface — simplest way to plot
FigureTop-level container — the whole window or page
AxesAn individual plot area with its own coordinate system
ArtistEverything you can see (Line2D, Text, Patch, etc.)
BackendsRendering engines: Agg (PNG), PDF, SVG, TkAgg, WebAgg…

Two interfaces: pyplot (stateful, MATLAB-style, good for quick scripts) and the OO API (explicit Figure/Axes objects, recommended for complex or embedded plots). This tutorial covers both.

02

The Figure / Axes Object Model

Understanding the hierarchy is the key to mastering Matplotlib.

LevelObjectWhat it is
1FigureThe entire window/canvas. Contains all Axes.
2AxesOne plot area (not to be confused with Axis/axes). Has x-axis, y-axis, title, data artists.
3AxisA single axis line (XAxis or YAxis) with ticks and labels.
4ArtistEverything rendered: lines, markers, text, patches, images.

pyplot style (stateful)

python
x = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 100)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 3))
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x), label='sin(x)')
plt.plot(x, np.cos(x), label='cos(x)')
plt.title('pyplot style')
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('y')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
▶ Output

OO style (explicit — recommended)

python
# Explicit Figure and Axes — preferred for complex plots
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 3))

ax.plot(x, np.sin(x), label='sin(x)')
ax.plot(x, np.cos(x), label='cos(x)')
ax.set_title('OO style')
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('y')
ax.legend()
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()
▶ Output

Rule of thumb: Use plt.xxx() for quick one-off plots. Use fig, ax = plt.subplots() whenever you need subplots, need to save programmatically, or embed in GUIs/web apps.

Anatomy of a Figure

pythonkey objects and their methods
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

# Figure-level
fig.set_size_inches(10, 5)
fig.set_facecolor('white')
fig.suptitle('Figure-level title', fontsize=14)

# Axes-level
ax.set_title('Axes title')
ax.set_xlabel('X Label')
ax.set_ylabel('Y Label')
ax.set_xlim(0, 10)
ax.set_ylim(-2, 2)
ax.set_facecolor('#f9f9f9')

# Retrieve axes from figure
axes_list = fig.get_axes()        # list of all Axes
current   = plt.gca()             # get current axes (pyplot)
curr_fig  = plt.gcf()             # get current figure (pyplot)

plt.show()

Line Plots

pythonbasic line plot with styling
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 200)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 4))

ax.plot(x, np.sin(x),
        color='#2055a8',
        linewidth=2,
        linestyle='-',
        label='sin(x)')

ax.plot(x, np.cos(x),
        color='#c94040',
        linewidth=1.5,
        linestyle='--',
        label='cos(x)')

ax.plot(x[:50], np.sin(x[:50]) * 0.5,
        color='#1a7a6e',
        linewidth=1,
        linestyle=':',
        marker='o',
        markersize=3,
        label='0.5·sin(x) sampled')

ax.set_title('Line Plot Showcase')
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('Amplitude')
ax.legend()
ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.show()
▶ Output

Format string shorthand

python
# [color][marker][linestyle] in a single format string
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 3))
x = np.linspace(0, 5, 20)

axes[0].plot(x, x,      'r-')   # red solid line
axes[1].plot(x, x**2,  'g--o') # green dashed + circle markers
axes[2].plot(x, x**0.5,'b:s')  # blue dotted + square markers

for a, t in zip(axes, ["'r-'","'g--o'","'b:s'"]):
    a.set_title(t)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Multiple lines & step plots

python
rng = np.random.default_rng(0)
days = np.arange(1, 8)
sales_a = [10, 14, 11, 18, 15, 20, 17]
sales_b = [8,  9,  13, 12, 16, 14, 19]

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(11, 4))

ax1.plot(days, sales_a, 'o-', label='Product A')
ax1.plot(days, sales_b, 's--', label='Product B')

# step plot — good for discrete events
ax2.step(days, sales_a, where='mid', label='Product A')
ax2.step(days, sales_b, where='mid', label='Product B', linestyle='--')
ax2.set_title('Step plot'); ax2.legend(); ax2.set_xlabel('Day')

Scatter Plots

pythonbasic scatter with size and color encoding
rng = np.random.default_rng(42)
n = 150
x  = rng.normal(0, 1, n)
y  = x * 0.5 + rng.normal(0, 0.8, n)
c  = rng.random(n)    # color mapped to colormap
s  = (rng.random(n) * 100) + 20   # size varies per point

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 5))
sc = ax.scatter(x, y,
                c=c,          # color — mapped through cmap
                s=s,          # marker size in points²
                cmap='viridis',
                alpha=0.75,
                edgecolors='white',
                linewidths=0.5)
fig.colorbar(sc, ax=ax, label='Random value')
ax.set_title('Scatter: size + color encoding')
ax.set_xlabel('X'); ax.set_ylabel('Y')
plt.show()
▶ Output

Scatter key parameters

ParameterDescription
cColor — can be single color, array of floats (→colormap), or array of colors
sMarker size in points² (area, not radius)
cmapColormap name (used when c is numeric)
vmin / vmaxClip colormap range
edgecolorsMarker edge color ('none' to disable)
alphaTransparency — helps with overplotting
markerMarker shape ('o','s','^', etc.)

Categorical scatter

python
categories = ['A', 'B', 'C']
colors     = ['#2055a8', '#c94040', '#1a7a6e']
rng = np.random.default_rng(7)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 4))
for cat, col in zip(categories, colors):
    xi = rng.normal(categories.index(cat), 0.4, 40)
    yi = rng.normal(categories.index(cat) * 0.5, 0.6, 40)
    ax.scatter(xi, yi, c=col, label=f'Class {cat}', alpha=0.7, s=40)

ax.legend(); ax.set_title('Categorical Scatter')
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Histograms & KDE

pythonhistogram
rng = np.random.default_rng(0)
data = rng.normal(100, 15, 1000)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(11, 4))

# Basic histogram
axes[0].hist(data, bins=30, color='#2055a8', edgecolor='white', alpha=0.85)
axes[0].set_title('Histogram (bins=30)')
axes[0].set_xlabel('Value'); axes[0].set_ylabel('Count')

# Density histogram + KDE overlay
axes[1].hist(data, bins=30, density=True, color='#c94040', alpha=0.5, edgecolor='white')
# KDE manually with scipy
from scipy.stats import gaussian_kde
kde = gaussian_kde(data)
xk  = np.linspace(data.min(), data.max(), 200)
axes[1].plot(xk, kde(xk), color='#c94040', lw=2.5)
axes[1].set_title('Density + KDE')
axes[1].set_xlabel('Value'); axes[1].set_ylabel('Density')

plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Histogram key parameters

ParameterDescriptionExample
binsNumber of bins or bin edgesbins=20 or bins=np.arange(50,150,5)
densityNormalize to probability densitydensity=True
cumulativeCumulative histogramcumulative=True
orientationHorizontal barsorientation='horizontal'
histtypeShape of bars'bar', 'step', 'stepfilled'
rangeClip data rangerange=(60, 140)

Multiple overlapping histograms

python
rng = np.random.default_rng(5)
g1 = rng.normal(100, 10, 500)
g2 = rng.normal(120, 15, 500)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))
ax.hist(g1, bins=30, alpha=0.6, color='#2055a8', label='Group A')
ax.hist(g2, bins=30, alpha=0.6, color='#c94040', label='Group B')
ax.axvline(g1.mean(), color='#2055a8', linestyle='--', lw=2, label=f'Mean A={g1.mean():.1f}')
ax.axvline(g2.mean(), color='#c94040', linestyle='--', lw=2, label=f'Mean B={g2.mean():.1f}')
ax.legend(); ax.set_title('Overlapping Histograms with Mean Lines')
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output
07

Pie Charts

python
labels  = ['Python', 'JavaScript', 'Java', 'C++', 'Other']
sizes   = [34, 25, 18, 12, 11]
explode = (0.06, 0, 0, 0, 0)   # pull out first slice
colors  = ['#2055a8','#c96820','#1a7a6e','#c94040','#9ab0cc']

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

# Standard pie
wedges, texts, autotexts = ax1.pie(
    sizes, explode=explode, labels=labels, colors=colors,
    autopct='%1.1f%%', pctdistance=0.8,
    shadow=False, startangle=90
)
for t in autotexts:
    t.set_fontsize(9); t.set_color('white')
ax1.set_title('Language Share')

# Donut chart — set a white circle in center
ax2.pie(sizes, labels=labels, colors=colors, autopct='%1.0f%%',
        startangle=90, pctdistance=0.8, wedgeprops=dict(width=0.55))
ax2.set_title('Donut Chart')

plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Design note: Pie charts are hard to read for more than 4-5 slices or similar-sized values. Prefer horizontal bar charts for comparisons.

Box & Violin Plots

pythonbox plots
rng = np.random.default_rng(1)
data = [rng.normal(mu, 1, 100) for mu in [5, 6, 5.5, 7]]
labels = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

# Box plot
bp = ax1.boxplot(data, labels=labels, patch_artist=True,
                 notch=True, vert=True)
colors = ['#c8d8f0','#f0c8c8','#c8f0dc','#f0e0c8']
for patch, color in zip(bp['boxes'], colors):
    patch.set_facecolor(color)
ax1.set_title('Box Plot (notched)'); ax1.set_ylabel('Value')

# Violin plot
parts = ax2.violinplot(data, positions=range(1, 5),
                       showmeans=True, showmedians=True)
for pc in parts['bodies']:
    pc.set_facecolor('#2055a8'); pc.set_alpha(0.5)
ax2.set_xticks(range(1, 5)); ax2.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax2.set_title('Violin Plot'); ax2.set_ylabel('Value')

plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Box plot anatomy

ElementMeaning
Box (IQR)25th–75th percentile (interquartile range)
Orange lineMedian (50th percentile)
Notch95% confidence interval around median
WhiskersDefault: 1.5 × IQR from box edges
Fliers (dots)Outliers beyond whiskers

Heatmaps & imshow

pythonimshow heatmap with annotations
data = np.array([
    [0.85, 0.12, 0.03],
    [0.07, 0.78, 0.15],
    [0.02, 0.18, 0.80],
])
row_labels = ['Cat', 'Dog', 'Bird']
col_labels = ['Cat', 'Dog', 'Bird']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 4))
im = ax.imshow(data, cmap='Blues', vmin=0, vmax=1)

# Add text annotations inside each cell
for i in range(len(row_labels)):
    for j in range(len(col_labels)):
        color = 'white' if data[i, j] > 0.5 else 'black'
        ax.text(j, i, f'{data[i,j]:.2f}', ha='center', va='center',
                color=color, fontsize=12)

ax.set_xticks(range(len(col_labels))); ax.set_xticklabels(col_labels)
ax.set_yticks(range(len(row_labels))); ax.set_yticklabels(row_labels)
ax.set_xlabel('Predicted'); ax.set_ylabel('Actual')
ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix')
fig.colorbar(im, ax=ax, shrink=0.8)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

pcolormesh — larger grids & continuous data

python
x = np.linspace(-3, 3, 100)
y = np.linspace(-3, 3, 100)
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
Z = np.exp(-(X**2 + Y**2))   # 2D Gaussian

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(11, 4))

im1 = ax1.pcolormesh(X, Y, Z, cmap='viridis', shading='auto')
fig.colorbar(im1, ax=ax1); ax1.set_title('pcolormesh: 2D Gaussian')

# Contour plot
cs = ax2.contourf(X, Y, Z, levels=15, cmap='RdYlBu_r')
ax2.contour(X, Y, Z, levels=15, colors='k', linewidths=0.5, alpha=0.5)
fig.colorbar(cs, ax=ax2); ax2.set_title('contourf + contour')

plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Subplots & Layouts

plt.subplots — grid of axes

python
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(12, 6))

x = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 100)
funcs = [np.sin, np.cos, np.tan,
         lambda x: np.sin(x)**2,
         lambda x: np.exp(-x/5) * np.sin(x),
         lambda x: x / (x**2 + 1)]
names = ['sin', 'cos', 'tan', 'sin²', 'damped sin', 'x/(x²+1)']

for ax, f, name in zip(axes.flat, funcs, names):
    ax.plot(x, f(x), lw=1.5)
    ax.set_title(name, fontsize=10)
    ax.set_ylim(-3, 3)
    ax.axhline(0, color='k', lw=0.5)

fig.suptitle('2×3 Subplot Grid', fontsize=14)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

subplot_mosaic — named, irregular layouts

python
# ASCII art layout — letter = axes name, same letter = span
layout = [
    ['top',  'top',  'right'],
    ['left', 'mid',  'right'],
]
fig, axs = plt.subplot_mosaic(layout, figsize=(10, 6),
                               constrained_layout=True)

x = np.linspace(0, 4 * np.pi, 200)
axs['top'].plot(x, np.sin(x)); axs['top'].set_title('top (wide)')
axs['left'].bar(['A','B','C'],[3,5,2]); axs['left'].set_title('left')
axs['mid'].scatter(*np.random.randn(2,40), alpha=0.5); axs['mid'].set_title('mid')
axs['right'].hist(np.random.randn(200), orientation='horizontal')
axs['right'].set_title('right (tall)')

fig.suptitle('subplot_mosaic layout')
plt.show()
▶ Output

GridSpec — precise layout control

python
from matplotlib.gridspec import GridSpec

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
gs  = GridSpec(2, 3, figure=fig, hspace=0.4, wspace=0.3)

ax_main  = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :2])   # row 0, cols 0-1 (wide)
ax_side  = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, 2])    # row 0, col 2
ax_bot1  = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0])    # row 1, col 0
ax_bot2  = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1])    # row 1, col 1
ax_bot3  = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 2])    # row 1, col 2

x = np.linspace(0, 6, 100)
ax_main.plot(x, np.sin(x)); ax_main.set_title('Main (wide)')
ax_side.bar(['A','B'], [3,5]); ax_side.set_title('Side')
for ax, t in zip([ax_bot1,ax_bot2,ax_bot3],['Bot1','Bot2','Bot3']):
    ax.scatter(*np.random.randn(2,20), s=15); ax.set_title(t)

plt.show()
▶ Output

Axes Customization

pythonticks, spines, grids, scales
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(11, 8))
x = np.linspace(0.1, 10, 200)

# 1. Log scale
ax = axes[0, 0]
ax.semilogy(x, np.exp(x/2), color='#2055a8')
ax.set_title('semilogy (log y)'); ax.set_xlabel('x'); ax.grid(True, which='both', alpha=0.3)

# 2. Custom ticks & labels
ax = axes[0, 1]
ax.plot(x, np.sin(x), color='#c94040')
ax.set_xticks([0, np.pi/2, np.pi, 3*np.pi/2, 2*np.pi])
ax.set_xticklabels(['0', 'π/2', 'π', '3π/2', '2π'])
ax.set_title('Custom tick labels')

# 3. Remove spines
ax = axes[1, 0]
ax.plot(x, np.cos(x), color='#1a7a6e')
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['left'].set_position(('outward', 8))
ax.spines['bottom'].set_position(('outward', 8))
ax.set_title('Minimal spines')

# 4. Grid customization + minor ticks
ax = axes[1, 1]
ax.plot(x, np.sin(x) + np.cos(2*x), color='#6a3fa0')
ax.minorticks_on()
ax.grid(True, which='major', linestyle='-',  alpha=0.4)
ax.grid(True, which='minor', linestyle=':',  alpha=0.2)
ax.tick_params(which='minor', length=3)
ax.tick_params(which='major', length=6)
ax.set_title('Major + minor grid')

plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Common axes methods reference

MethodDescription
ax.set_xlim(a, b)Set x range
ax.set_ylim(a, b)Set y range
ax.set_xscale('log')Log scale ('linear', 'log', 'symlog', 'logit')
ax.set_xticks(list)Explicitly set tick positions
ax.set_xticklabels(list)Set tick labels (can include LaTeX)
ax.tick_params(...)Style ticks: direction, length, color, labelsize
ax.minorticks_on()Enable minor ticks
ax.grid(True, ...)Show/style gridlines
ax.axhline(y)Horizontal reference line
ax.axvline(x)Vertical reference line
ax.axhspan(y1,y2)Horizontal shaded band
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)Hide a spine
ax.invert_xaxis()Flip x axis

Annotations & Text

python
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 200)
y = np.sin(x)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 4))
ax.plot(x, y, color='#2055a8', lw=2)

# Simple text
ax.text(1.5, 0.9, 'Peak region', fontsize=10, color='gray')

# Arrow annotation
ax.annotate('Global max\n(π/2, 1)',
            xy=(np.pi/2, 1),       # point to annotate
            xytext=(3, 0.7),          # text location
            arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->', color='#c94040', lw=1.5),
            fontsize=9, color='#c94040')

# Annotate a zero crossing
ax.annotate('Zero crossing',
            xy=(np.pi, 0),
            xytext=(np.pi + 0.5, 0.5),
            arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->', color='#1a7a6e'),
            fontsize=9, color='#1a7a6e')

# Shaded region
ax.axhspan(-0.2, 0.2, alpha=0.15, color='gold', label='±0.2 band')

# Math text (LaTeX)
ax.set_title(r'$f(x) = \sin(x)$ with annotations')
ax.set_xlabel(r'$x$'); ax.set_ylabel(r'$f(x)$')
ax.legend(); ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

Colormaps

Colormaps map scalar data to colors. Choosing the right colormap matters for clarity and accessibility.

CategoryExamplesUse for
Sequentialviridis, plasma, Blues, YlOrRdOrdered numeric data (0 → max)
DivergingRdBu, coolwarm, bwr, PiYGData with meaningful midpoint (e.g. ± deviation)
Cyclichsv, twilightData that wraps (e.g. phase, angle)
Qualitativetab10, Set1, PairedCategorical / discrete labels
Perceptually uniformviridis, cividis, infernoPrint/colorblind-safe
pythoncolormaps in practice
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(13, 4))

x = np.linspace(-2, 2, 80)
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, x)
Z_seq = X**2 + Y**2                 # sequential (0+)
Z_div = X**2 - Y**2                 # diverging (±)
Z_ang = np.arctan2(Y, X) / np.pi    # cyclic (-1 to 1)

for ax, Z, cmap, title in zip(
    axes,
    [Z_seq, Z_div, Z_ang],
    ['viridis', 'coolwarm', 'twilight'],
    ['Sequential: viridis', 'Diverging: coolwarm', 'Cyclic: twilight']
):
    im = ax.pcolormesh(X, Y, Z, cmap=cmap, shading='auto')
    fig.colorbar(im, ax=ax, shrink=0.8)
    ax.set_title(title)

plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ Output

Twin Axes & Secondary Y

months  = np.arange(1, 13)

Animations

pythonFuncAnimation — update each frame
from matplotlib.animation import FuncAnimation

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 3))
x = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 200)
line, = ax.plot(x, np.sin(x), lw=2)   # initial state

ax.set_xlim(0, 2 * np.pi)
ax.set_ylim(-1.3, 1.3)
ax.set_title('Animated sine wave')

def update(frame):
    line.set_ydata(np.sin(x + frame / 10))   # shift phase each frame
    return line,

anim = FuncAnimation(
    fig, update,
    frames=100,          # number of frames
    interval=50,          # ms between frames
    blit=True             # only redraw changed artists (faster)
)

# In Jupyter: displays inline
# from IPython.display import HTML; HTML(anim.to_jshtml())

# Save as GIF or MP4
anim.save('sine_wave.gif', writer='pillow', fps=20)
# anim.save('sine_wave.mp4', writer='ffmpeg', fps=20)

plt.show()
▶ Output
(animated GIF: sine wave scrolling right as phase increases each frame)

ArtistAnimation — pre-computed frames

python
from matplotlib.animation import ArtistAnimation

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 3))
x = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 200)

frames = []
for phase in np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 30):
    line, = ax.plot(x, np.sin(x + phase), color='#2055a8', lw=2)
    frames.append([line])

ax.set_xlim(0, 2 * np.pi); ax.set_ylim(-1.5, 1.5)
anim = ArtistAnimation(fig, frames, interval=80, blit=True)
plt.show()
▶ Output
(pre-computed animation: 30 frames of shifting sine phase)

Use FuncAnimation for memory-efficient animations where each frame is computed on demand. Use ArtistAnimation when frames are pre-computed and memory is not a concern.

Backends & Jupyter

A backend handles rendering (drawing) and display. Matplotlib auto-selects one, but you can override.

BackendTypeUse case
AggNon-interactive (file)Servers, scripts — writes PNG/PDF/SVG files
TkAggInteractive GUIDesktop apps using Tkinter
Qt5AggInteractive GUIDesktop apps using Qt5
WebAggInteractive (browser)Remote servers, JupyterLab
nbAgg / widgetInteractive (Jupyter)JupyterLab/Notebook inline + pan/zoom
inlineNon-interactive (Jupyter)Jupyter Notebook — static PNG inline
python
import matplotlib
print(matplotlib.get_backend())     # current backend

# Switch backend (must be before importing pyplot)
matplotlib.use('Agg')               # non-interactive, file only
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# In Jupyter — magic commands
%matplotlib inline     # static images inline (PNG)
%matplotlib widget     # interactive ipympl widget
%matplotlib notebook   # interactive (older notebooks)

# plt.show() behavior:
# - In script: opens GUI window, blocks until closed
# - In Jupyter inline: no-op (cell output shows figure)
# - With Agg backend: no window, must use savefig()

Performance Tips

TipDetails
Use plt.close(fig) after savingFigures stay in memory until explicitly closed. Close after savefig() in loops.
Use blit=True in animationsOnly redraws changed artists — 5–10× speedup for animations.
Prefer Agg for batch scriptsNon-interactive backend is faster; no GUI overhead.
Downsample before plottingFor > 100K points, downsample or use rasterized=True.
Use set_data() to updateFaster than re-creating line objects in loops or animations.
Avoid unnecessary redrawsUse plt.draw() not plt.show() in update loops.
Use fig.canvas.draw_idle()Deferred redraw — only redraws when needed by GUI event loop.
pythonefficient batch figure generation
import matplotlib
matplotlib.use('Agg')   # non-interactive — much faster for batch
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

for i in range(10):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 3))
    ax.plot(np.random.randn(100).cumsum())
    ax.set_title(f'Simulation {i}')
    fig.savefig(f'sim_{i}.png', dpi=100, bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.close(fig)   # ← critical: free memory

print('All 10 figures saved.')
▶ Output
All 10 figures saved.

Rasterize dense scatter

python
# For 1M+ point scatter in a PDF/SVG — rasterize to avoid huge file
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.scatter(np.random.randn(100_000), np.random.randn(100_000),
           s=1, alpha=0.1,
           rasterized=True)   # raster this layer, rest stays vector
fig.savefig('scatter.pdf')

Common Pitfalls & Gotchas

PitfallSymptomFix
Axes ≠ axisConfusion between Axes (plot area) and Axis (x or y line)ax = the plot; ax.xaxis = the x line
Forgetting plt.show()Script exits with no visible outputAlways call plt.show() at end of script (not needed in Jupyter inline)
Memory leak in loopsRAM usage grows unboundedlyCall plt.close(fig) after saving each figure
Overwriting current figureplt.plot() on wrong figureUse OO API: fig, ax = plt.subplots() and always call ax.plot()
Labels clipped when savingTitle/xlabel cut off in saved fileUse bbox_inches='tight' in savefig()
Wrong number of colors in cycleColors repeat before expectedSet ax.set_prop_cycle() or use explicit color= for each line
Log scale with zeros/negativesValueError or missing dataUse symlog scale or clip/offset data before log
tight_layout warningsWarning about incompatibility with constrained_layoutUse either tight_layout() OR constrained_layout=True — not both
Interactive plot freezesGUI blocks in interactive modeUse plt.pause(0.001) in update loops or switch to non-blocking mode
Backend must be set firstmatplotlib.use() error after importCall matplotlib.use('Agg') before import matplotlib.pyplot

Pitfall: pyplot state machine confusion

python
# ❌ Problematic — implicit state, easy to plot on wrong axes
plt.figure()
plt.plot([1,2,3], [4,5,6])
# ... many lines later ...
plt.title('My plot')   # which figure does this target?

# ✅ Explicit OO API — always clear
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot([1,2,3], [4,5,6])
ax.set_title('My plot')   # unambiguously on this ax
plt.show()

Exercise 3 — Annotate a peak

Plot y = x·e^(−x²/4) for x ∈ [−5, 5]. Find and annotate the global maximum with an arrow.

pythonanswer
x = np.linspace(-5, 5, 500)
y = x * np.exp(-x**2 / 4)

peak_x = x[np.argmax(y)]
peak_y = y.max()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))
ax.plot(x, y, color='#2055a8', lw=2)
ax.axhline(0, color='gray', lw=0.5)

ax.annotate(
    f'Max = ({peak_x:.2f}, {peak_y:.2f})',
    xy=(peak_x, peak_y),
    xytext=(peak_x + 1.5, peak_y - 0.2),
    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->', lw=1.5, color='#c94040'),
    fontsize=10, color='#c94040',
    bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.3', facecolor='#ffe8e8', edgecolor='#c94040')
)
ax.scatter([peak_x], [peak_y], color='#c94040', zorder=5)
ax.set_title(r'$y = x \cdot e^{-x^2/4}$ with peak annotation')
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

Exercise 4 — Dual-axis revenue chart

Given monthly revenue and units sold, plot revenue as bars (left y-axis) and units as a line (right y-axis).

pythonanswer
months  = np.arange(1, 13)
revenue = [80,90,100,120,135,150,145,165,180,195,215,240]
units   = [40,45,48,55,62,70,66,75,82,88,98,110]

fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 4))
c1, c2 = '#2055a8', '#c94040'

ax1.bar(months, revenue, color=c1, alpha=0.6, label='Revenue ($K)')
ax1.set_ylabel('Revenue ($K)', color=c1)
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=c1)
ax1.set_xticks(months)
ax1.set_xlabel('Month')

ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(months, units, 'o-', color=c2, lw=2, label='Units Sold')
ax2.set_ylabel('Units Sold', color=c2)
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=c2)

h1, l1 = ax1.get_legend_handles_labels()
h2, l2 = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()
ax1.legend(h1 + h2, l1 + l2, loc='upper left')
ax1.set_title('Revenue & Units — Dual Axis')
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
